 how Kundalini may spontaneously rise in a layman with no sadhan=\r\na, while many serious sadhakas may not experience it.\n=C2=A0\nFirstly, Kunda=\r\nlini rise is NOT an achievement. It is just A SMALL\n STEP in overcoming one=\r\n&#39;s current limited identity.\n=C2=A0\nLet me give an analogy. One wanting to =\r\nmove from one&#39;s small dilapidated house (this\n body-mind complex) to a huge=\r\n palace (realized Self) may first construct the palace over time and move i=\r\nnto it when it is COMPLETE. Alternately, if one occasionally goes and stays=\r\n in the palace still under construction (analogy for out of body experience=\r\ns due to Kundalini rise), is it an achievement? In fact, it comes with risk=\r\ns. The former approach is safer and one loses nothing in it. Similarly, one=\r\n can progress towards complete Self-realization without any out of body exp=\r\neriences. These are not my word&#39;s, but Maharshi Vasishtha&#39;s words to Lord R=\r\nama.\n=C2=A0\nSecondly, one does not get something without wanting it and put=\r\nting sufficient effort towards it. One may have deeply desired a Kundalini =\r\nrise in a previous life and may have put enough effort. As a result, one ma=\r\ny be getting it now. But one may be unprepared (and ironically may not even=\r\n want it!) when it comes in this life.\n=C2=A0\nAs you do sadhana, try not to=\r\n fancy too many specific\n desires. Nature has a delay mechanism in granting=\r\n your desires (because of constraints on what Nature can give you right now=\r\n, arising from YOUR\n OWN previous actions). So Nature sometimes gives you w=\r\nhat you want LATE, when you no longer want it or want something else. For e=\r\nxample, one may pray for great wealth one&#39;s whole life and be born as a ric=\r\nh but very sick man in next life. One may not enjoy that wealth and pray wh=\r\nole life for health. In the life after that, one may be very healthy, but n=\r\not have any knowledge or money. In another \ncase, one may deeply desire to =\r\nact in a famous film. One may be reborn \nas a tiger or a dog and act in a f=\r\namous film, but not really enjoy that \nexperience. Basically, people keep g=\r\noing in circles through various lives, always &quot;seeking&quot; something they are =\r\n&quot;missing&quot;.\n=C2=A0\nAnyway, coming back to Kundalini, if one deeply desires a=\r\nn out of body experience given by a rising Kundalini and one&#39;s previous kar=\r\nmas constrain one from having it in THIS life, one may be born in next life=\r\n with this specific desire destined to fructify (if there is enough karmik =\r\nforce behind it).\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0\n *\n=C2=A0\nKundalini rise is not nec=\r\nessarily scary or painful, if one is well-prepared in terms of attitude and=\r\n detachment.\n=C2=A0\nOnce I saw a chipmunk glued to a mouse trap. I went to =\r\nfree it and it panicked so badly and started to shake violently. I went to =\r\nsave it from a certain slow death and it was scared that I would kill it!\n=\r\n=C2=A0\nWe are like that chipmunk, glued to the mouse trap called this body-=\r\nmind complex and scared of being rescued from a certain slow death!\n=C2=A0\n=\r\nIf our ideas about who we are (viz this current body-mind complex) are inco=\r\nrrect and if we are this &quot;infinite Self&quot; as shastras say, won&#39;t a complete =\r\nrealization of that at some stage involve stepping out of this body-mind co=\r\nmplex, without being scared?\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nKundalini rise =\r\nafter most undesirable conditioning is overcome, is far better than\n Kundal=\r\nini rise forced when some really undesirable conditioning is still left in =\r\none&#39;s system.\n=C2=A0\nWhen one transcends one problematic notion about who o=\r\nne is and what one needs, another notion that lay buried deeper in consciou=\r\nsness may spring to the surface and torment one. If one overcomes the notio=\r\nn &quot;I am the body&quot;, there may be another notion in one&#39;s body-mind complex t=\r\nhat one&#39;s awareness clings on to (e.g. a great doctor, a great leader, a gr=\r\neat scholar, a great saint etc). As an extreme example, if one person had a=\r\n hidden deep desire to be a great soul who rescues the world, he may fancy =\r\nthat he is a re-incarnated X or Y who will rescue the world now. When one&#39;s=\r\n self-awareness (i.e. Kundalini!) deeply clings to any such notion, it can =\r\ncause havoc. The person may show some signs of progress and yet remain in i=\r\ngnorance and get stuck badly.\n=C2=A0\nAn awakened Kundalini in a system with=\r\n undesirable conditioning may accentuate one&#39;s weaknesses and wrong notions=\r\n heavily and cause serious psychiatric and spiritual problems.\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nThe best approach I recommend is to NOT think in terms o=\r\nf Kundalini and its rise. Just do sadhana, overcome your\n weaknesses and im=\r\nprove your detachment over time. Again, I want to emphasize that detachment=\r\n is not disgust or distaste for life/things/people around you. Disgust is t=\r\nhe other side of coin of attachment. It is a negative attachment.\n=C2=A0\n\nD=\r\non&#39;t worry about \nwhether your Kundalini rises or not. Worry about whether =\r\nyou are able to resist 6 internal enemies (shadripus) and 8 bondages (ashta=\r\n pashas) or \nnot. If your ability to resist them is increasing, you are mak=\r\ning progress. EVEN IF your Kundalini is fast asleep, you are still making p=\r\nrogress. When you completely overcome them, Kundalini (your self-awareness)=\r\n \nwill automatically ascend to the top and meet Her Lord (true Self).\n=C2=\r\n=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nOne word o